 of the antique in different parts of Italy, as well as examining other, less widely studied antiquarian traditions in France, the Netherlands, Spain, Portugal, Britain and Poland. They consider how real or fictive ruins, inscriptions and literary works were used to demonstrate a particular idea of local origins, to rewrite history or to vaunt civic pride. In doing so, they tackle such varied subjects as municipal antiquities collections in Southern Italy and France, the antiquarian response to the pagan, Christian and Islamic past on the Iberian Peninsula, and Netherlandish interest in megalithic ruins thought to be traces of a prehistoric race of Giants.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEurope-History. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  aClassical tradition.  aEuropean antiquarianism.  aRenaissance antiquarianism.  aRenaissance art and architecture.  aRenaissance history.  aRenaissance literature.  aRenaissance reception of antiquity.  aearly modern archaeology.  aearly modern historiography.1 aArciszewska, Barbara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBenelli, Francesco, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChristian, Kathleen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChristian, Kathleen, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDe Jonge, Krista, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDivitiis, Bianca de, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFigueiredo, João R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMargolis, Oren, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMarías, Fernando, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOlds, Katrina B., econtributor.4ctb4https